message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. Among the options, dysplastic cells extending into the lamina propria is the worse finding because it suggests a higher grade and stage of bladder cancer. It means the abnormal cells have invaded the deeper layers of the bladder, making it more difficult to treat and with a worse prognosis. The other options indicate bladder cancer but do not necessarily suggest a worse prognosis.

The presence of dysplastic cells extending into the lamina propria indicates invasion of the underlying tissue and is associated with the poorest prognosis. Nests of atypical cells in the urothelium suggest carcinoma in situ, which is also associated with a poor prognosis. Friable urothelium with ulcerations and disordered urothelium lined with papillary fronds are less indicative of malignancy and have a better prognosis.
